ag Aonghuis</b> or <b>Mag Aonghusa</b> ‘son of <i>Aonghus</i>’ (see   Angus  ). This is the surname of a chieftain family in western County Down. Compare the Scottish form   McInnis  , and the variant   McNeese  . Compare also   McGuinness  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Magennis had at least 3 sons with Brian Macaedo O'Neill, Prince of Tyrone. She died on 7 February 1337, in Skerry, County Antrim, Ireland."},"et":{"–7 February 1337":"–7. veebruar 1337","1264–1354":"1264–1354","1290–1359":"1290–1359","1291–1345":"1291–1345","1300–1347":"1300–1347","–1337":"–1337","7 February 1337":"7. v